adrFiles.status: > A decision may be "proposed" if it hasn't been agreed upon yet, or "accepted" once it is agreed upon. If a later ADR changes or reverses a decision, it may be marked as "deprecated" or "superseded" with a reference to its replacement. {Deprecated|Proposed|Accepted}

The two points above have been implemented; the `config.js` has a Google Analytics identifier and the documentation workflow has been up and running largely without problems for several months. Details about the documentation build & workflow can be found [here](../DOCS_README.md)

Declined **Until there's more stability/motivation/use-cases/demand, the decision is to push this entirely application side and just have apps which want events to be provable to insert them into their application-side merkle trees. Of course this puts more pressure on their application state and makes event proving application specific, but it might help built up a better sense of use-cases and how this ought to ultimately be done by Tendermint.**
